Examples     Fallback content  The simplest way to render a default error message.    import   {   ErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 < ErrorBoundary   fallback = { < div > Something went wrong </ div > } >   
  < YourApplication   />   
 </ ErrorBoundary > ;

Examples     Render props   Render prop function responsible for returning a fallback UI based on a thrown value.    import   {   ErrorBoundary ,   getErrorMessage   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 < ErrorBoundary   
  fallbackRender = { ( {   error ,   resetErrorBoundary   } )   =>   (   
    < div   role = "alert" >   
      < p > Something went wrong: </ p >   
      < pre   style = { {   color :   "red"   } } > { getErrorMessage ( error ) } </ pre >   
      < button   onClick = { resetErrorBoundary } > Retry </ button >   
    </ div >   
  ) }   
  onReset = { ( details )   =>   {   
    // Reset the state of your app so the error doesn't happen again   
  } }   
 >   
  < YourApplication   />   
 </ ErrorBoundary > ;

Examples     Fallback component  React component responsible for returning a fallback UI based on a thrown value.    import   {   ErrorBoundary ,   getErrorMessage ,   type   FallbackProps   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   Fallback ( {   error ,   resetErrorBoundary   } :   FallbackProps )   {   
  return   (   
    < div   role = "alert" >   
      < p > Something went wrong: </ p >   
      < pre   style = { {   color :   "red"   } } > { getErrorMessage ( error ) } </ pre >   
      < button   onClick = { resetErrorBoundary } > Retry </ button >   
    </ div >   
  ) ;   
 }   

 < ErrorBoundary   
  FallbackComponent = { Fallback }   
  onReset = { ( details )   =>   {   
    // Reset the state of your app so the error doesn't happen again   
  } }   
 >   
  < YourApplication   />   
 </ ErrorBoundary > ;

Examples     Error logging  Use the onError callback to log errors to a service like Sentry.    import   type   {   ErrorInfo   }   from   "react" ;   
 import   {   ErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   logError ( error :   unknown ,   info :   ErrorInfo )   {   
  // Do something with the error, e.g. log to an external API   
 }   

 < ErrorBoundary   FallbackComponent = { ErrorFallback }   onError = { logError } >   
  < YourApplication   />   
 </ ErrorBoundary > ;

Examples     Async user code errors  React only handles errors thrown during render or during component lifecycle methods (e.g. effects and did-mount/did-update). Errors thrown in event handlers, or after async code has run, will not be caught. The useErrorBoundary hook can be used to pass those errors to the nearest error boundary:    import   {   useErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   useUserProfileInfo ( {   username   } :   {   username :   string   } )   {   
  const   {   showBoundary   }   =   useErrorBoundary ( ) ;   

  useEffect ( ( )   =>   {   
    fetchGreeting ( username ) . then (   
      ( response )   =>   {   
        // Set data in state and re-render ...   
      } ,   
      ( error )   =>   {   
        // Show error boundary   
        showBoundary ( error ) ;   
      }   
    ) ;   
  } ) ;   
 }

Examples     Reset nearest boundary  The useErrorBoundary hook can be used to reset the nearest error boundary and retry a failed render attempt.    import   {   useErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   Example ( )   {   
  const   {   resetBoundary   }   =   useErrorBoundary ( ) ;   

  // Call resetBoundary() to reset the nearest ErrorBoundary and retry a failed render   
 }

API     useErrorBoundary hook  Convenience hook for imperatively showing or dismissing error boundaries.    import   {   useErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   Example ( )   {   
  const   {   
    // The currently visible Error (if one has been thrown).   
    error ,   

    // Method to reset and retry the nearest active error boundary (if one is active).   
    resetBoundary ,   

    // Trigger the nearest error boundary to display the error provided.   
    showBoundary ,   
   }   =   useErrorBoundary ( ) ;   

  // ...   
 }          This hook must only be used within an ErrorBoundary subtree.

API     withErrorBoundary HOC  This package can also be used as a higher-order component. For example, given a component like this:    function   UserProfile ( {   username   } :   {   username :   string   } )   {   
  // Render...   
 }    You could use the withErrorBoundary HOC to create a wrapper component:    import   {   withErrorBoundary   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 const   UserProfileWithErrorBoundary   =   withErrorBoundary ( UserProfile ,   {   
  fallback :   < div > Something went wrong </ div > ,   
  onError ( error ,   info )   {   
    // Do something with the error   
    // E.g. log to an error logging client here   
  } ,   
 } ) ;    And then render it like this    < UserProfileWithErrorBoundary   username = "Brian"   /> ;    This might be useful for certain types of reusable/library components.

API     getErrorMessage helper  Typically thrown errors in JavaScript are instances of type Error, but this is not always the case. Any value can be thrown- strings, numbers, even null or undefined. To simplify working with thrown values, this library exports a utility method called getErrorMessage.    import   {   getErrorMessage ,   type   FallbackProps   }   from   "react-error-boundary" ;   

 function   Fallback ( {   error   } :   FallbackProps )   {   
  // Because 'error' can be anything, it's safest not to assume it's an Error   
  // Use the getErrorMessage helper method to extract the message instead.   
  const   message   =   getErrorMessage ( error )   ??   "Unknown error" ;   

  // Render fallback UI...   
 }

Common questions    Why didn't the boundary catch my error?    This package is built on top of React error boundaries, so it has all of the advantages and constraints of that API. This means that it can't catch errors during:  Server side rendering Event handlers Asynchronous code (including effects)  You can show an error boundary for asynchronous code, but you have to catch the error yourself. Learn more.     ErrorBoundary cannot be used as a JSX component   This error can be caused by a version mismatch between react and @types/react. To fix this, ensure that both match exactly. For NPM, you may need to use an override:    {   
  "overrides" :   {   
    "@types/react" :   "17.0.60"   
  }   
 }    Yarn has a similar mechanism called a resolution:    {   
  "resolutions" :   {   
    "@types/react" :   "17.0.60"   
  }   
 }      Unable to resolve path to module 'react-error-boundary'   The version 6.0 release of this library switched to ESM-only to better work with modern JavaScript tooling. If your project uses a framework or runtime that does not yet support ES Modules (like Expo or Hermes) then you should use version 5 of this library. There are no major API differences between these two versions other than ESM support.
